      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from E William Colglazier (National Academy of Sciences) comments on criticism of National Research Council draft study on fuel economy in July 19 editorial on global warming</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Clueless on Global Warming'' (editorial, July 19) discusses a draft study on fuel economy standards by the National Research Council, the operating arm of the National Academy of Sciences and the National Academy of Engineering.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="online_lead_paragraph">
        <p>t To the Editor</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Clueless on Global Warming'' (editorial, July 19) discusses a draft study on fuel economy standards by the National Research Council, the operating arm of the National Academy of Sciences and the National Academy of Engineering.</p>
        <p>First, we believe that it is critical to mention that the draft study is not a final report of the National Academies. It does not carry the weight of a final, peer-reviewed study from our independent nongovernmental institution.</p>
        <p>Second, we disagree with your statement that the committee ''was  dominated by industry representatives.'' We posted this committee for public comment and determined that no member has a conflict of interest.  No one is appointed to an academy committee as a representative of any interest group. The brief biographies of the members of this highly expert committee are publicly available, and the final report is expected to be issued in late July.</p>
        <p>E. WILLIAM COLGLAZIER  Executive Officer  National Academy of Sciences  Washington, July 19, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
